# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: threadx-rtos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A **microcontroller** (**MC**, **uC**, or **μC**) or **microcontroller unit** (**MCU**) is a small computer on a single integrated circuit.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A microcontroller contains one or more processor cores along with memory and programmable input/output peripherals.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Program memory in the form of NOR flash, OTP ROM, or ferroelectric RAM is also often included on the chip, as well as a small amount of RAM.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are designed for embedded applications, in contrast to the microprocessors used in personal computers or other general-purpose applications consisting of various discrete chips.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In modern terminology, a microcontroller is similar to, but less sophisticated than, a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A SoC may include a microcontroller as one of its components but usually integrates it with advanced peripherals like a graphics processing unit (GPU), a Wi-Fi module, or one or more coprocessors.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are used in automatically controlled products and devices, such as automobile engine control systems, implantable medical devices, remote controls, office machines, appliances, power tools, toys, and other embedded systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] By reducing the size and cost compared to a design that uses a separate microprocessor, memory, and input/output devices, microcontrollers make digital control of more devices and processes practical.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Mixed-signal microcontrollers are common, integrating analog components needed to control non-digital electronic systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In the context of the Internet of things, microcontrollers are an economical and popular means of data collection, sensing and actuating the physical world as edge devices.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers may use four-bit words and operate at frequencies as low as 4 kHz for low power consumption (single-digit milliwatts or microwatts).
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] They generally have the ability to retain functionality while waiting for an event such as a button press or other interrupt; power consumption while sleeping (with the CPU clock and most peripherals off) may be just nanowatts, making many of them well suited for long lasting battery applications.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Other microcontrollers may serve performance-critical roles, where they may need to act more like a digital signal processor (DSP), with higher clock speeds and power consumption.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released on a single MOS LSI chip in 1971.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] It was followed by the 4-bit Intel 4040, the 8-bit Intel 8008, and the 8-bit Intel 8080.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] All of these processors required several external chips to implement a working system, including memory and peripheral interface chips.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] As a result, the total system cost was several hundred (1970s US) dollars, making it impossible to economically computerize small appliances.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] MOS Technology introduced its sub-$100 microprocessors in 1975, the 6501 and 6502.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Their chief aim was to reduce this cost barrier but these microprocessors still required external support, memory, and peripheral chips which kept the total system cost in the hundreds of dollars.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] One book credits TI engineers Gary Boone and Michael Cochran with the successful creation of the first microcontroller in 1971.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The result of their work was the TMS 1000, which became commercially available in 1974.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] It combined read-only memory, read/write memory, processor and clock on one chip and was targeted at embedded systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] During the early-to-mid-1970s, Japanese electronics manufacturers began producing microcontrollers for automobiles, including 4-bit MCUs for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, and dashboard, and 8-bit MCUs for engine control.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Partly in response to the existence of the single-chip TMS 1000, Intel developed a computer system on a chip optimized for control applications, the Intel 8048, with commercial parts first shipping in 1977.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] It combined RAM and ROM on the same chip with a microprocessor.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Among numerous applications, this chip would eventually find its way into over one billion PC keyboards.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Valenter, stated that the microcontroller was one of the most successful products in the company's history, and he expanded the microcontroller division's budget by over 25%.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Most microcontrollers at this time had concurrent variants.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] One had EPROM program memory, with a transparent quartz window in the lid of the package to allow it to be erased by exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] These erasable chips were often used for prototyping.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The other variant was either a mask-programmed ROM or a PROM variant which was only programmable once.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] For the latter, sometimes the designation *OTP* was used, standing for "one-time programmable".
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In an OTP microcontroller, the PROM was usually of identical type as the EPROM, but the chip package had no quartz window; because there was no way to expose the EPROM to ultraviolet light, it could not be erased.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Because the erasable versions required ceramic packages with quartz windows, they were significantly more expensive than the OTP versions, which could be made in lower-cost opaque plastic packages.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] For the erasable variants, quartz was required, instead of less expensive glass, for its transparency to ultraviolet light—to which glass is largely opaque—but the main cost differentiator was the ceramic package itself.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] **Piggyback microcontrollers** were also used.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In 1993, the introduction of EEPROM memory allowed microcontrollers (beginning with the Microchip PIC16C84) to be electrically erased quickly without an expensive package as required for EPROM, allowing both rapid prototyping, and in-system programming.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] (EEPROM technology had been available prior to this time, but the earlier EEPROM was more expensive and less durable, making it unsuitable for low-cost mass-produced microcontrollers.) The same year, Atmel introduced the first microcontroller using Flash memory, a special type of EEPROM.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Other companies rapidly followed suit, with both memory types.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Nowadays microcontrollers are cheap and readily available for hobbyists, with large online communities around certain processors.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In 2002, about 55% of all CPUs sold in the world were 8-bit microcontrollers and microprocessors.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Over two billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 1997, and according to Semico, over four billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 2006.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] More recently, Semico has claimed the MCU market grew 36.5% in 2010 and 12% in 2011.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A typical home in a developed country is likely to have only four general-purpose microprocessors but around three dozen microcontrollers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A typical mid-range automobile has about 30 microcontrollers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] They can also be found in many electrical devices such as washing machines, microwave ovens, and telephones.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Cost to manufacture can be under US$0.10 per unit.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Cost has plummeted over time, with the cheapest 8-bit microcontrollers being available for under US$0.03 in 2018, and some 32-bit microcontrollers around US$1 for similar quantities.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In 2012, following a global crisis—a worst ever annual sales decline and recovery and average sales price year-over-year plunging 17%—the biggest reduction since the 1980s—the average price for a microcontroller was US$0.88 (US$0.69 for 4-/8-bit, US$0.59 for 16-bit, US$1.76 for 32-bit).
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In 2012, worldwide sales of 8-bit microcontrollers were around US$4 billion, while 4-bit microcontrollers also saw significant sales.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] On 21 June 2018, the "world's smallest computer" was announced by the University of Michigan.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Because they are too small to have conventional radio antennae, they receive and transmit data with visible light.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A microcontroller can be considered a self-contained system with a processor, memory and peripherals and can be used as an embedded system.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The majority of microcontrollers in use today are embedded in other machinery, such as automobiles, telephones, appliances, and peripherals for computer systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] While some embedded systems are very sophisticated, many have minimal requirements for memory and program length, with no operating system, and low software complexity.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Typical input and output devices include switches, relays, solenoids, LEDs, small or custom liquid-crystal displays, radio frequency devices, and sensors for data such as temperature, humidity, light level etc.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Embedded systems usually have no keyboard, screen, disks, printers, or other recognizable I/O devices of a personal computer, and may lack human interaction devices of any kind.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers must provide real-time (predictable, though not necessarily fast) response to events in the embedded system they are controlling.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Possible interrupt sources are device-dependent and often include events such as an internal timer overflow, completing an analog-to-digital conversion, a logic-level change on an input such as from a button being pressed, and data received on a communication link.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Where power consumption is important as in battery devices, interrupts may also wake a microcontroller from a low-power sleep state where the processor is halted until required to do something by a peripheral event.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Typically microcontroller programs must fit in the available on-chip memory, since it would be costly to provide a system with external, expandable memory.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Compilers and assemblers are used to convert both high-level and assembly language code into a compact machine code for storage in the microcontroller's memory.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Depending on the device, the program memory may be permanent, read-only memory that can only be programmed at the factory, or it may be field-alterable flash or erasable read-only memory.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Manufacturers have often produced special versions of their microcontrollers in order to help the hardware and software development of the target system.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Originally these included EPROM versions that have a "window" on the top of the device through which program memory can be erased by ultraviolet light, ready for reprogramming after a programming ("burn") and test cycle.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Since 1998, EPROM versions are rare and have been replaced by EEPROM and flash, which are easier to use (can be erased electronically) and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Other versions may be available where the ROM is accessed as an external device rather than as internal memory, however these are becoming rare due to the widespread availability of cheap microcontroller programmers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The use of field-programmable devices on a microcontroller may allow field update of the firmware or permit late factory revisions to products that have been assembled but not yet shipped.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Programmable memory also reduces the lead time required for deployment of a new product.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Where hundreds of thousands of identical devices are required, using parts programmed at the time of manufacture can be economical.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] These "mask-programmed" parts have the program laid down in the same way as the logic of the chip, at the same time.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A customized microcontroller incorporates a block of digital logic that can be personalized for additional processing capability, peripherals and interfaces that are adapted to the requirements of the application.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers usually contain from several to dozens of general purpose input/output pins (GPIO).
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] GPIO pins are software configurable to either an input or an output state.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] When GPIO pins are configured to an input state, they are often used to read sensors or external signals.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Configured to the output state, GPIO pins can drive external devices such as LEDs or motors, often indirectly, through external power electronics.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Many embedded systems need to read sensors that produce analog signals.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] However, because they are built to interpret and process digital data, i.e.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] 1s and 0s, they are not able to do anything with the analog signals that may be sent to it by a device.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] So, an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) is used to convert the incoming data into a form that the processor can recognize.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A less common feature on some microcontrollers is a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that allows the processor to output analog signals or voltage levels.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In addition to the converters, many embedded microprocessors include a variety of timers as well.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] One of the most common types of timers is the programmable interval timer (PIT).
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A PIT may either count down from some value to zero, or up to the capacity of the count register, overflowing to zero.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Once it reaches zero, it sends an interrupt to the processor indicating that it has finished counting.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] This is useful for devices such as thermostats, which periodically test the temperature around them to see if they need to turn the air conditioner on/off, the heater on/off, etc.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A dedicated pulse-width modulation (PWM) block makes it possible for the CPU to control power converters, resistive loads, motors, etc., without using many CPU resources in tight timer loops.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A universal asynchronous receiver/transmitter (UART) block makes it possible to receive and transmit data over a serial line with very little load on the CPU.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Dedicated on-chip hardware also often includes capabilities to communicate with other devices (chips) in digital formats such as Inter-Integrated Circuit (I²C), Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI), Universal Serial Bus (USB), and Ethernet.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers may not implement an external address or data bus as they integrate RAM and non-volatile memory on the same chip as the CPU.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Using fewer pins, the chip can be placed in a much smaller, cheaper package.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Integrating the memory and other peripherals on a single chip and testing them as a unit increases the cost of that chip, but often results in decreased net cost of the embedded system as a whole.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] This integration drastically reduces the number of chips and the amount of wiring and circuit board space that would be needed to produce equivalent systems using separate chips.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Furthermore, on low pin count devices in particular, each pin may interface to several internal peripherals, with the pin function selected by software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] This allows a part to be used in a wider variety of applications than if pins had dedicated functions.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers have proved to be highly popular in embedded systems since their introduction in the 1970s.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers use a Harvard architecture: separate memory buses for instructions and data, allowing accesses to take place concurrently.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Where a Harvard architecture is used, instruction words for the processor may be a different bit size than the length of internal memory and registers; for example: 12-bit instructions used with 8-bit data registers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The decision of which peripheral to integrate is often difficult.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The microcontroller vendors often trade operating frequencies and system design flexibility against time-to-market requirements from their customers and overall lower system cost.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Manufacturers have to balance the need to minimize the chip size against additional functionality.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontroller architectures vary widely.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Some designs include general-purpose microprocessor cores, with one or more ROM, RAM, or I/O functions integrated onto the package.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Other designs are purpose-built for control applications.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A microcontroller instruction set usually has many instructions intended for bit manipulation (bit-wise operations) to make control programs more compact.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] For example, a general-purpose processor might require several instructions to test a bit in a register and branch if the bit is set, where a microcontroller could have a single instruction to provide that commonly required function.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers historically have not had math coprocessors, so floating-point arithmetic has been performed by software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] However, some recent designs do include FPUs and DSP-optimized features.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] An example would be Microchip's PIC32 MIPS-based line.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers were originally programmed only in assembly language, but various high-level programming languages, such as C, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Compilers for general-purpose languages will typically have some restrictions as well as enhancements to better support the unique characteristics of microcontrollers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers have environments to aid developing certain types of applications.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontroller vendors often make tools freely available to make it easier to adopt their hardware.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Microcontrollers with specialty hardware may require their own non-standard dialects of C, such as SDCC for the 8051, which prevent using standard tools (such as code libraries or static analysis tools) even for code unrelated to hardware features.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Interpreters may also contain nonstandard features, such as MicroPython, although a fork, CircuitPython, has looked to move hardware dependencies to libraries and have the language adhere to a more CPython standard.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Interpreter firmware is also available for some microcontrollers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] For example, BASIC on the early microcontroller Intel 8052; BASIC and FORTH on the Zilog Z8 as well as some modern devices.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Typically these interpreters support interactive programming.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Simulators are available for some microcontrollers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] These allow a developer to analyze what the behavior of the microcontroller and their program should be if they were using the actual part.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A simulator will show the internal processor state and also that of the outputs, as well as allowing input signals to be generated.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] While on the one hand most simulators will be limited from being unable to simulate much other hardware in a system, they can exercise conditions that may otherwise be hard to reproduce at will in the physical implementation, and can be the quickest way to debug and analyze problems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Recent microcontrollers are often integrated with on-chip debug circuitry that when accessed by an in-circuit emulator (ICE) via JTAG, allow debugging of the firmware with a debugger.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A real-time ICE may allow viewing and/or manipulating of internal states while running.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A tracing ICE can record executed program and MCU states before/after a trigger point.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Many others exist, some of which are used in very narrow range of applications or are more like applications processors than microcontrollers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The microcontroller market is extremely fragmented, with numerous vendors, technologies, and markets.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Note that many vendors sell or have sold multiple architectures.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In contrast to general-purpose computers, microcontrollers used in embedded systems often seek to optimize interrupt latency over instruction throughput.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Issues include both reducing the latency, and making it be more predictable (to support real-time control).
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] When an electronic device causes an interrupt, during the context switch the intermediate results (registers) have to be saved before the software responsible for handling the interrupt can run.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] They must also be restored after that interrupt handler is finished.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] If there are more processor registers, this saving and restoring process may take more time, increasing the latency.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Another technique involves spending silicon gates on "shadow registers": One or more duplicate registers used only by the interrupt software, perhaps supporting a dedicated stack.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Lower end microcontrollers tend to support fewer interrupt latency controls than higher end ones.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Two different kinds of memory are commonly used with microcontrollers, a non-volatile memory for storing firmware and a read–write memory for temporary data.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] From the earliest microcontrollers to today, six-transistor SRAM is almost always used as the read/write working memory, with a few more transistors per bit used in the register file.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] In addition to the SRAM, some microcontrollers also have internal EEPROM and/or NVRAM for data storage; and ones that do not have any (such as the BASIC Stamp), or where the internal memory is insufficient, are often connected to an external EEPROM or flash memory chip.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] A few microcontrollers beginning in 2003 have "self-programmable" flash memory.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] The earliest microcontrollers used mask ROM to store firmware.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Later microcontrollers (such as the early versions of the Freescale 68HC11 and early PIC microcontrollers) had EPROM memory, which used a translucent window to allow erasure via UV light, while production versions had no such window, being OTP (one-time-programmable).
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Firmware updates were equivalent to replacing the microcontroller itself, thus many products were not upgradeable.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Motorola MC68HC805 was the first microcontroller to use EEPROM to store the firmware.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] EEPROM microcontrollers became more popular in 1993 when Microchip introduced PIC16C84 and Atmel introduced an 8051-core microcontroller that was first one to use NOR Flash memory to store the firmware.
[src:threadx-rtos/microcontroller] Today's microcontrollers almost all use flash memory, with a few models using FRAM and some ultra-low-cost parts still using OTP or mask ROM.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Founded in 1975 by Bill Gates and Paul Allen to market BASIC interpreters for the Altair 8800, Microsoft rose to dominate the PC operating system market with MS-DOS in the mid-1980s, followed by Windows.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company's 1986 initial public offering (IPO) and subsequent rise in its share price created three billionaires and an estimated 12,000 millionaires among Microsoft employees.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Since the 1990s, it has increasingly diversified its business.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Steve Ballmer replaced Gates as CEO in 2000.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] He oversaw the then-largest of Microsoft's corporate acquisitions in Skype Technologies in 2011, an increased focus on hardware that led to its first in-house PC line—the Surface—in 2012, and the formation of Microsoft Mobile through Nokia.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Since Satya Nadella became CEO in 2014, the company has changed focus towards cloud computing and acquired LinkedIn in 2016.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Under his direction, the company has expanded its video gaming business to support the Xbox brand, establishing the Microsoft Gaming division in 2022 and acquiring Activision Blizzard in 2023.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft has been dominant in the IBM PC–compatible operating system and office software suite markets since the 1990s.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Its best-known software products are the Windows line of operating systems and the Microsoft Office and Microsoft 365 suite of productivity applications, which most notably include the Word word processor, Excel spreadsheet editor, and PowerPoint presentation program.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Its flagship hardware products are the Surface lineup of PCs and the Xbox brand of video game consoles, the latter including the Xbox network.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company also provides a range of consumer Internet services such as Bing web search, the MSN web portal, the Outlook.com (Hotmail) email service, and the Microsoft Store.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In the enterprise and development fields, Microsoft most notably provides the Azure cloud computing platform, Microsoft SQL Server database software, and Visual Studio.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft became the third publicly traded U.S. company to be valued at over $1 trillion in April 2019.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] It has been criticized for monopolistic practices, and the company's software received criticism for problems with ease of use, robustness, and security.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft has also been criticized for its role in providing services to Israel during the Gaza war.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Childhood friends Bill Gates and Paul Allen sought to make a business using their skills in computer programming.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 1972, they founded Traf-O-Data, which sold a rudimentary computer to track and analyze automobile traffic data.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The January 1975 issue of *Popular Electronics* featured Micro Instrumentation and Telemetry Systems's (MITS) Altair 8800 microcomputer, which inspired Allen to suggest that they could program a BASIC interpreter for the device.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Gates called MITS and claimed that he had a working interpreter, and MITS requested a demonstration.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Allen worked on a simulator for the Altair while Gates developed the interpreter, and it worked flawlessly when they demonstrated it to MITS in March 1975 in Albuquerque, New Mexico.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] MITS agreed to distribute it, marketing it as Altair BASIC.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Gates and Allen established Microsoft on April 4, 1975, with Gates as CEO, and Allen suggested the name "Micro-Soft", short for micro-computer software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In August 1977, the company formed an agreement with ASCII Magazine in Japan, resulting in its first international office of ASCII Microsoft.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft moved its headquarters to Bellevue, Washington, in January 1979.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft entered the operating system (OS) business in 1980 with its own version of Unix, licensed from AT&T Corporation a year before, called Xenix, but it was MS-DOS that solidified the company's dominance.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] IBM awarded a contract to Microsoft in November 1980 to provide a version of the CP/M OS to be used in the IBM Personal Computer (IBM PC).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] For this deal, Microsoft purchased a CP/M clone called 86-DOS from Seattle Computer Products which it branded as MS-DOS, although IBM rebranded it to IBM PC DOS.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft retained ownership of MS-DOS following the release of the IBM PC in August 1981.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] IBM had copyrighted the IBM PC BIOS, so other companies had to reverse engineer it for non-IBM hardware to run as IBM PC compatibles, but no such restriction applied to the operating systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company expanded into new markets with the release of the Microsoft Mouse in 1983, as well as with a publishing division named Microsoft Press.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Paul Allen resigned from Microsoft in 1983 after developing Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft released Windows 1.0 on November 20, 1985, as a graphical extension for MS-DOS, despite having begun jointly developing OS/2 with IBM that August.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft released its version of OS/2 to original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) on April 2, 1987.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 1990, the Federal Trade Commission examined Microsoft for possible collusion due to the partnership with IBM, marking the beginning of more than a decade of legal clashes with the government.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Meanwhile, the company was at work on Microsoft Windows NT, which was heavily based on its copy of the OS/2 code.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] It shipped on July 21, 1993, with a new modular kernel and the 32-bit Win32 application programming interface (API), making it easier to port from 16-bit (MS-DOS-based) Windows.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft informed IBM of Windows NT, and the OS/2 partnership deteriorated.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 1990, Microsoft introduced the Microsoft Office suite which bundled separate applications such as Microsoft Word and Microsoft Excel.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On May 22, Microsoft launched Windows 3.0, featuring streamlined user interface graphics and improved protected mode capability for the Intel 386 processor, and both Office and Windows became dominant in their respective areas.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Following Bill Gates's internal "Internet Tidal Wave memo" on May 26, 1995, Microsoft began to redefine its offerings and expand its product line into computer networking and the World Wide Web.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] With a few exceptions of new companies, like Netscape, Microsoft was the only major and established company that acted fast enough to be a part of the World Wide Web practically from the start.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Other companies like Borland, WordPerfect, Novell, IBM and Lotus, being much slower to adapt to the new situation, would give Microsoft market dominance.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company released Windows 95 on August 24, 1995, featuring pre-emptive multitasking, a completely new user interface with a novel start button, and 32-bit compatibility; similar to NT, it provided the Win32 API.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Windows 95 came bundled with the online service MSN, which was intended to be a competitor to services such as CompuServe and AOL.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The web browser Internet Explorer was not bundled with the retail release of Windows 95, and was instead included in the later Microsoft Plus! pack, as well as with OEM releases of Windows 95.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Backed by a high-profile marketing campaign and what *The New York Times* called "the splashiest, most frenzied, most expensive introduction of a computer product in the industry's history," Windows 95 quickly became a success.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Branching out into new markets in 1996, Microsoft and General Electric's NBC unit created a new 24/7 cable news channel, MSNBC.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft created Windows CE 1.0, a new OS designed for devices with low memory and other constraints, such as personal digital assistants.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In October 1997, the Justice Department filed a motion in the Federal District Court, stating that Microsoft violated an agreement signed in 1994 and asked the court to stop the bundling of Internet Explorer with Windows.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On January 13, 2000, Bill Gates handed over the CEO position to Steve Ballmer, an old college friend of Gates and employee of the company since 1980, while creating a new position for himself as Chief Software Architect.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Under Ballmer's leadership, the company saw an increased focus on hardware products.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On October 25, 2001, Microsoft released Windows XP, unifying the mainstream and NT lines of OS under the NT codebase.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company released the Xbox later that year, entering the video game console market dominated by Sony and Nintendo.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In November 2005, the company's second and most successful video game console, the Xbox 360, was released.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Increasingly present in the hardware business following Xbox, Microsoft 2006 released the Zune series of digital media players, a successor of its previous software platform Portable Media Center.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Released in January 2007, the next version of Windows, Vista, focused on features, security and a redesigned user interface dubbed Aero.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft Office 2007, released at the same time, featured a "Ribbon" user interface which was a significant departure from its predecessors.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Relatively strong sales of both products helped to produce a record profit in 2007.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The European Union imposed another fine of €899 million ($1.4 billion) for Microsoft's lack of compliance with the March 2004 judgment on February 27, 2008, saying that the company charged rivals unreasonable prices for key information about its workgroup and backoffice servers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft stated that it was in compliance and that "these fines are about the past issues that have been resolved".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Gates retired from his role as Chief Software Architect on June 27, 2008, a decision announced in June 2006, while retaining other positions related to the company in addition to being an advisor for the company on key projects.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Azure Services Platform, the company's entry into the cloud computing market for Windows, launched on October 27, 2008.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On February 12, 2009, Microsoft announced its intent to open a chain of Microsoft-branded retail stores, and on October 22, 2009, the first retail Microsoft Store opened in Scottsdale, Arizona; the same day Windows 7 was officially released to the public.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As the smartphone industry boomed in the late 2000s, Microsoft had struggled to keep up with its rivals in providing a modern smartphone operating system, falling behind Apple and Google-sponsored Android in the United States.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As a result, in 2010 Microsoft revamped its aging flagship mobile operating system, Windows Mobile, replacing it with the new Windows Phone OS that was released in October that year.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] It used a new user interface design language, codenamed "Metro", which prominently used simple shapes, typography, and iconography, utilizing the concept of minimalism.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft implemented a new strategy for the software industry, providing a consistent user experience across all smartphones using the Windows Phone OS.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] It launched an alliance with Nokia in 2011 and Microsoft worked closely with the company to co-develop Windows Phone, but remained partners with long-time Windows Mobile OEM HTC.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft is a founding member of the Open Networking Foundation started on March 23, 2011.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] This nonprofit organization is focused on providing support for a cloud computing initiative called Software-Defined Networking.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The initiative is meant to speed innovation through simple software changes in telecommunications networks, wireless networks, data centers, and other networking areas.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Following the release of Windows Phone, Microsoft undertook a gradual rebranding of its product range throughout 2011 and 2012, with the corporation's logos, products, services, and websites adopting the principles and concepts of the Metro design language.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft unveiled Windows 8, an operating system designed to power both personal computers and tablet computers, in Taipei in June 2011.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Also in 2011, Microsoft saw its largest acquisition by taking over Skype.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The Surface was unveiled in June 2012, becoming the first computer in the company's history to have its hardware made by Microsoft.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On June 25, Microsoft paid US$1.2 billion to buy the social network Yammer.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On July 31, it launched the Outlook.com webmail service to compete with Gmail.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On September 4, 2012, Microsoft released Windows Server 2012.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In July 2012, Microsoft sold its 50% stake in MSNBC, which it had run as a joint venture with NBC since 1996.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In October 2012, Microsoft launched Windows 8, Microsoft Surface, and Windows Phone 8.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] To cope with the potential for an increase in demand for products and services, Microsoft opened a number of "holiday stores" across the U.S. to complement the increasing number of "bricks-and-mortar" Microsoft Stores that opened in 2012.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On March 29, 2013, Microsoft launched a Patent Tracker.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In August 2012, the New York City Police Department announced a partnership with Microsoft for the development of the Domain Awareness System which is used for police surveillance in New York City.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The Kinect, a motion-sensing input device made by Microsoft and designed as a video game controller, first introduced in November 2010, was upgraded for the 2013 release of the Xbox One video game console.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On July 19, 2013, Microsoft stocks suffered its biggest one-day percentage sell-off since the year 2000, after its fourth-quarter report raised concerns among investors on the poor showings of both Windows 8 and the Surface tablet.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft suffered a loss of more than US$32 billion.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In line with the maturing PC business, in July 2013, Microsoft announced that it would reorganize into four new business divisions: Operating Systems, Apps, Cloud, and Devices.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] All previous divisions were dissolved into new divisions without any workforce cuts.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On September 3, 2013, Microsoft agreed to buy Nokia's mobile unit for $7 billion, following Amy Hood taking the role of CFO.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On February 4, 2014, Steve Ballmer stepped down as CEO of Microsoft and was succeeded by Satya Nadella, who previously led Microsoft's Cloud and Enterprise division.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Thompson took on the role of chairman, in place of Bill Gates, who continued to participate as a technology advisor.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Thompson became the second chairman in Microsoft's history.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On April 25, 2014, Microsoft acquired Nokia Devices and Services for $7.2 billion.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] This new subsidiary was renamed Microsoft Mobile Oy.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On September 15, 2014, Microsoft acquired the video game development company Mojang, best known for *Minecraft*, for $2.5 billion.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Since Nadella became CEO, the company has changed focus towards cloud computing.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On January 21, 2015, Microsoft announced the release of its first interactive whiteboard, named Surface Hub.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On July 29, 2015, Windows 10 was released, with its server sibling, Windows Server 2016, released in September 2016.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft's share of the U.S. smartphone market in January 2016 was 2.7%.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] During the summer of 2015 the company lost $7.6 billion related to its mobile-phone business, firing 7,800 employees.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 2015, the construction of a data center in Mecklenburg County, Virginia, led to the destruction of a historic African American cemetery despite archeological recommendations for preservation.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On March 1, 2016, Microsoft announced the merger of its PC and Xbox divisions, with Phil Spencer announcing that Universal Windows Platform (UWP) apps would be the focus for Microsoft's gaming in the future.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft also aqcuired LinkedIn in 2016.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On January 24, 2017, Microsoft showcased Intune for Education at the BETT 2017 education technology conference in London.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Intune for Education is a new cloud-based application and device management service for the education sector.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In May 2016, the company announced it was laying off 1,850 workers, and taking an impairment and restructuring charge of $950 million.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In June 2016, Microsoft announced a project named Microsoft Azure Information Protection.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] It aims to help enterprises protect their data as it moves between servers and devices.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In November 2016, Microsoft joined the Linux Foundation as a Platinum member during Microsoft's Connect(); developer event in New York.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The cost of each Platinum membership is US$500,000 per year.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Some analysts had deemed this unthinkable ten years prior, however, as in 2001 then-CEO Steve Ballmer called Linux "cancer".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In January 2018, Microsoft patched Windows 10 to account for CPU problems related to Intel's Meltdown security breach.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The patch led to issues with the Microsoft Azure virtual machines reliant on Intel's CPU architecture.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On January 12, Microsoft released PowerShell Core 6.0 for the macOS and Linux operating systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In February 2018, Microsoft ceased notification support for its Windows Phone devices which effectively ended firmware updates for the discontinued devices.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In March 2018, Microsoft recalled Windows 10 S to change it to a mode for the Windows operating system rather than a separate and unique operating system.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In March the company also established guidelines that censor users of Office 365 from using profanity in private documents.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In April 2018, Microsoft released the source code for Windows File Manager under the MIT License to celebrate the program's 20th anniversary.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In April the company further expressed willingness to embrace open source initiatives by announcing Azure Sphere as its own derivative of the Linux operating system.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In May 2018, Microsoft partnered with 17 American intelligence agencies to develop cloud computing products.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The project is dubbed "Azure Government" and has ties to the Joint Enterprise Defense Infrastructure (JEDI) surveillance program.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On June 4, 2018, Microsoft officially announced the acquisition of GitHub for $7.5 billion, a deal that closed on October 26, 2018.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On July 10, 2018, Microsoft revealed the Surface Go platform to the public.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] A free version of Teams was released on July 12, 2018.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In August 2018, Microsoft released two projects called Microsoft AccountGuard and Defending Democracy.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] It also unveiled Snapdragon 850 compatibility for Windows 10 on the ARM architecture.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for Internet of things (IoT) technologies related to water management.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In September 2018, Microsoft discontinued Skype Classic.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On October 10, 2018, Microsoft joined the Open Invention Network community despite holding more than 60,000 patents.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, an open source release of the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) core used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The project promotes the idea of Firmware as a Service.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In the same month, Microsoft announced the open source implementation of Windows Forms and the Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) which will allow for further movement of the company toward the transparent release of key frameworks used in developing Windows desktop applications and software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] December also saw the company discontinue the Microsoft Edge [Legacy] browser project in favor of the "New Edge" browser project, featuring a Chromium based backend.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In February 2019, hundreds of Microsoft employees protested the company's war profiteering from a $480 million contract to develop virtual reality headsets for the United States Army.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On August 5, 2020, Microsoft stopped its xCloud game streaming test for iOS devices.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Apple imposed a strict limit on "remote desktop clients" which means applications are only allowed to connect to a user-owned host device or gaming console owned by the user.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On September 21, 2020, Microsoft announced its intent to acquire video game company ZeniMax Media, the parent company of Bethesda Softworks.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On March 9, 2021, the acquisition was finalized at $8.1 billion and ZeniMax Media became part of Microsoft's Xbox Game Studios division.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On November 10, 2020, Microsoft released the Xbox Series X and Xbox Series S video game consoles.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In February 2021, Microsoft released Azure Quantum for public preview.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The public cloud computing platform provides access to quantum software and quantum hardware including trapped ion, neutral atom, and superconducting systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In April 2021, Microsoft announced it would buy Nuance Communications for approximately $16 billion, completing the acquisition in March 2022.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 2021, in part due to the strong quarterly earnings spurred by the COVID-19 pandemic, Microsoft's valuation came to nearly $2 trillion.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The increased necessity for remote work and distance education drove demand for cloud computing and grew the company's gaming sales.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On June 24, 2021, Microsoft announced Windows 11 during a livestreamed event.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The announcement came with confusion after Microsoft announced Windows 10 would be the last version of the operating system.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] It was released to the general public on October 5, 2021.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In September 2021, it was announced that the company had acquired TakeLessons, an online platform that connects students and tutors in numerous subjects.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The acquisition positioned Microsoft to grow its presence in the market of providing online education to large numbers of people.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In the same month, Microsoft acquired Australia-based video editing software company Clipchamp.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In October 2021, Microsoft announced that it began rolling out end-to-end encryption (E2EE) support for Microsoft Teams calls in order to secure business communication while using video conferencing software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On October 7, Microsoft acquired Ally.io, a software service that measures companies' progress against OKRs, planning to incorporate it into its Viva family of employee experience products.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On January 18, 2022, Microsoft announced the acquisition of American video game developer and holding company Activision Blizzard in an all-cash deal worth $68.7 billion, which was completed in 2023.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft also named Phil Spencer, head of the Xbox brand since 2014, the inaugural CEO of the newly established Microsoft Gaming division, which now houses the Xbox operations team and the three publishers in the company's portfolio (Xbox Game Studios, ZeniMax Media, Activision Blizzard).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft had not released statements regarding Activision's recent legal controversies regarding employee abuse, but reports have alleged that Activision CEO Bobby Kotick, a major target of the controversy, would leave the company after the acquisition is finalized.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The deal was closed on October 13, 2023.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In January 2023, CEO Satya Nadella announced Microsoft would lay off 10,000 employees.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The announcement came a day after hosting a Sting concert for 50 people, including Microsoft executives, in Davos, Switzerland.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On January 23, 2023, Microsoft announced a new multi-year, multi-billion dollar investment deal with ChatGPT developer OpenAI.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In June 2023, Microsoft released Azure Quantum Elements to run molecular simulations and calculations in computational chemistry and materials science using a combination of AI, high-performance computing and quantum computing.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The service includes Copilot, a GPT-4 based large language model tool to query and visualize data, write code, initiate simulations, and educate researchers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] At a November 2023 developer conference, Microsoft announced two new custom-designed computing chips: The Maia chip, designed to run large language models, and Cobalt CPU, designed to power general cloud services on Azure.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On November 20, 2023, Satya Nadella announced that Sam Altman, who had been ousted as CEO of OpenAI just days earlier, and Greg Brockman, who had resigned as president, would join Microsoft to lead a new advanced AI research team.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] However, the plan was short-lived, as Altman was subsequently reinstated as OpenAI's CEO and Brockman rejoined the company amid pressure from OpenAI's employees and investors on its board.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In March 2024, Inflection AI's cofounders Mustafa Suleyman and Karen Simonyan announced their departure from the company in order to start Microsoft AI, with Microsoft acqui-hiring nearly the entirety of its 70-person workforce.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As part of the deal, Microsoft paid Inflection $650 million to license its technology.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In January 2024, Microsoft became the most valued publicly traded company.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Meanwhile, that month, the company announced a subscription offering of artificial intelligence for small businesses via Copilot Pro.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In June 2024, Microsoft announced it would be laying off 1,000 employees from the company's mixed reality and Azure cloud computing divisions.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The same month, Microsoft announced that it was building a "hyperscale data centre" in South East Leeds.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In July 2024, it was reported that the company was laying off its diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) team.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On July 19, a global IT outage impacted Microsoft services, affecting businesses, airlines, and financial institutions worldwide.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The outage was traced back to a flawed update of CrowdStrike's cybersecurity software, which resulted in Microsoft systems crashing and causing disruptions across various sectors.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Despite CrowdStrike's CEO George Kurtz clarifying that the issue was not a cyberattack, the incident had widespread consequences, leading to delays in air travel, financial transactions, and medical services globally.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft stated that the underlying cause had been fixed but acknowledged ongoing residual impacts on some Microsoft 365 apps and services.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In September 2024, BlackRock and Microsoft announced a $30 billion fund, the Global AI Infrastructure Investment Partnership, to invest in AI infrastructure such as data centers and energy projects.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Partners include Abu Dhabi-backed MGX and Nvidia, which will provide AI expertise.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Investments will primarily focus on the U.S., with some in partner countries.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft also announced relaunch of its controversial tool, Recall, in November 2024 after addressing privacy concerns.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Initially criticized for taking regular screenshots without user consent, Recall was changed to an opt-in feature instead of being default on.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The UK's Information Commissioner's Office monitored the situation and noted the adjustments, which included enhanced security measures like encryption and biometric access.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] While experts regarded these changes as improvements, they advised caution, with some recommending further testing before users opted in.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On February 28, 2025, Microsoft announced that Skype would be shutting down on May 5, 2025, to streamline its focus on Microsoft Teams.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company stated there would be no job cuts due to the shutdown.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In mid-2025, Microsoft's Russian division, Microsoft Rus LLC, filed for bankruptcy after President Vladimir Putin stated that foreign services providers should be throttled in Russia to make way for domestic software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company had restructured operations in Russia after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, but those restructuring efforts had failed.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On May 23, 2025, it was reported that Europol's European Cybercrime Centre worked with Microsoft to disrupt Lumma Stealer, a significant infostealer threat.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The joint operation targeted a sophisticated ecosystem that allowed criminals to exploit stolen information on a massive scale.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On July 2, 2025, Microsoft announced it would cut nearly 4% of its workforce, around 9,000 jobs, to control costs amid heavy AI infrastructure spending, while also restructuring management and streamlining operations.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] According to an analysis by Bridgewater Associates, Microsoft—along with Amazon, Alphabet and Meta—is expected to collectively invest about $650 billion to scale up AI-related infrastructure in 2026.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In March 2026, Microsoft-controlled discussion forums banned the nickname *Microslop*, used to express pushback against Microsoft's Copilot-based and GenAI efforts.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In March 2026, Microsoft signed an energy pledge at the White House which required it to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power its data centers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On 9 March 2026, Microsoft unveiled the Copilot Cowork tool, which is based on Claude Cowork, tapping into the growing demand for autonomous agents.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] 14 in the 2022 *Fortune* 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue; and it was the world's largest software maker by revenue in 2022 according to *Forbes* Global 2000.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 2018, Microsoft became the most valuable publicly traded company in the world, a position it has repeatedly traded with Apple in the years since.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In April 2019, Microsoft became the third U.S. public company to be valued at over $1 trillion.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As of 2024, Microsoft has the third-highest global brand valuation.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft is one of only two U.S.-based companies that have a prime credit rating of AAA.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The company is run by a board of directors made up of mostly company outsiders, as is customary for publicly traded companies.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Members of the board of directors as of December 2023 are Satya Nadella, Reid Hoffman, Hugh Johnston, Teri List, Sandi Peterson, Penny Pritzker, Carlos Rodriguez, Charles Scharf, John W.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Thompson, Emma Walmsley and Padmasree Warrior.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Board members are elected every year at the annual shareholders' meeting using a majority vote system.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] There are four committees within the board that oversee more specific matters.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On March 13, 2020, Gates announced that he is leaving the board of directors of Microsoft and Berkshire Hathaway to focus more on his philanthropic efforts.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] When Microsoft went public and launched its initial public offering (IPO) in 1986, the opening stock price was $21; after the trading day, the price closed at $27.75.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As of July 2010, with the company's nine stock splits, any IPO shares would be multiplied by 288; if one were to buy the IPO today, given the splits and other factors, it would cost about 9 cents.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The stock price peaked in 1999 at around $119 ($60.928, adjusting for splits).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Though the company had subsequent increases in dividend payouts, the price of Microsoft's stock remained steady for years.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Standard & Poor's and Moody's Investors Service have both given a AAA rating to Microsoft, whose assets were valued at $41 billion as compared to only $8.5 billion in unsecured debt.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Consequently, in February 2011 Microsoft released a corporate bond amounting to $2.25 billion with relatively low borrowing rates compared to government bonds.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] For the first time in 20 years Apple Inc. surpassed Microsoft in Q1 2011 quarterly profits and revenues due to a slowdown in PC sales and continuing huge losses in Microsoft's Online Services Division (which contains its search engine Bing).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft profits were $5.2 billion, while Apple Inc. profits were $6 billion, on revenues of $14.5 billion and $24.7 billion respectively.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft's Online Services Division has been continuously loss-making since 2006 and in Q1 2011 it lost $726 million.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] This follows a loss of $2.5 billion for the year 2010.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On July 20, 2012, Microsoft posted its first quarterly loss ever, despite earning record revenues for the quarter and fiscal year, with a net loss of $492 million due to a writedown related to the advertising company aQuantive, which had been acquired for $6.2 billion back in 2007.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As of January 2014, Microsoft's market capitalization stood at $314B, making it the 8th-largest company in the world by market capitalization.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In November 2014, Microsoft overtook ExxonMobil to become the second most-valuable company by market capitalization, behind only Apple Inc.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Its total market value was over $410B—with the stock price hitting $50.04 a share, the highest since early 2000.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 2015, Reuters reported that Microsoft had earnings abroad of $76.4 billion which were untaxed by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Under U.S. law, corporations do not pay income tax on overseas profits until the profits are brought into the United States.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In November 2018, the company won a $480 million military contract with the U.S. government to bring augmented reality (AR) headset technology into the weapon repertoires of American soldiers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The two-year contract may result in follow-on orders of more than 100,000 headsets, according to documentation describing the bidding process.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] One of the contract's tag lines for the augmented reality technology seems to be its ability to enable "25 bloodless battles before the 1st battle", suggesting that actual combat training is going to be an essential aspect of the augmented reality headset capabilities.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As such, it needs subsidiaries present in whatever national markets it chooses to harvest.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] An example is Microsoft Canada, which it established in 1985.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Other countries have similar installations, to funnel profits back up to Redmond and to distribute the dividends to the holders of MSFT stock.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In FY 2025, Microsoft spent over 25 billion dollars on marketing, or over 15 % of its expenses, compared to over 30 billion dollars spent on research and development.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft employed over 40 thousand people in marketing and sales.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Another study, released by the Open Source Development Labs, claimed that the Microsoft studies were "simply outdated and one-sided" and its survey concluded that the TCO of Linux was lower due to Linux administrators managing more servers on average and other reasons.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In July 2014, Microsoft announced plans to lay off 18,000 employees.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft employed 127,104 people as of June 5, 2014, making this about a 14 percent reduction of its workforce as the biggest Microsoft layoff ever.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] This included 12,500 professional and factory personnel.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Previously, Microsoft had eliminated 5,800 jobs in 2009 in line with the Great Recession of 2008–2017.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In September 2014, Microsoft laid off 2,100 people, including 747 people in the Seattle–Redmond area, where the company is headquartered.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The firings came as a second wave of the layoffs that were previously announced.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] This brought the total number to over 15,000 out of the 18,000 expected cuts.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In October 2014, Microsoft revealed that it was almost done with eliminating 18,000 employees, which was its largest-ever layoff sweep.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In July 2015, Microsoft announced another 7,800 job cuts in the next several months.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In May 2016, Microsoft announced another 1,850 job cuts mostly in its Nokia mobile phone division.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] As a result, the company will record an impairment and restructuring charge of approximately $950 million, of which approximately $200 million will relate to severance payments.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft laid off 1,900 employees in its gaming division in January 2024.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The layoffs primarily affected Activision Blizzard employees, but some Xbox and ZeniMax employees were also affected.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Blizzard president Mike Ybarra and chief design officer Allen Adham also resigned.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In May 2025, Microsoft announced that it is laying off more than 6,000 employees, around three percent of the company's entire workforce.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In July 2025, Microsoft announced another round of layoffs, cutting approximately 9,000 employees in its largest workforce reduction in over two years.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The cuts affected multiple divisions, including Xbox, with 830 positions eliminated at its Redmond, Washington headquarters.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Amid the layoffs, Microsoft also closed its office in Pakistan and laid off its employees there as part of its move toward a software-as-a-service and AI operating model.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft recognizes seven trade unions representing 1,750 workers in the United States at its video game subsidiaries Activision Blizzard and ZeniMax Media.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] U.S. workers have been vocal in opposing military and law-enforcement contracts with Microsoft.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Bethesda Game Studios is unionized in Canada.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft South Korea has recognized its union since 2017.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] German employees have elected works councils since 1998.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft provides information about reported bugs in its software to intelligence agencies of the United States government, prior to the public release of the fix.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] A Microsoft spokesperson stated that the corporation runs several programs that facilitate the sharing of such information with the U.S. government.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Following media reports about PRISM, NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in May 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including Microsoft.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] According to leaks of said program, Microsoft joined the PRISM program in 2007.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] During the first six months of 2013, Microsoft received requests that affected between 15,000 and 15,999 accounts.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In December 2013, the company made a statement to further emphasize that it takes its customers' privacy and data protection very seriously, saying that "government snooping potentially now constitutes an 'advanced persistent threat,' alongside sophisticated malware and cyber attacks".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The statement also marked the beginning of three-part program to enhance Microsoft's encryption and transparency efforts.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In April 2016, the company sued the U.S. government, argued that secrecy orders were preventing the company from disclosing warrants to customers in violation of the company's and customers' rights.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On October 23, 2017, Microsoft said it would drop the lawsuit as a result of a policy change by the United States Department of Justice (DoJ).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] In 2022 Microsoft shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Amazon, Google, and Oracle.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] On a Friday afternoon in January 2024, Microsoft disclosed that a Russian state-sponsored group hacked into its corporate systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] The group, accessed "a very small percentage" of Microsoft corporate email accounts, which also included members of its senior leadership team and employees in its cybersecurity and legal teams.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p01] Microsoft noted in a blog post that the attack might have been prevented if the accounts in question had enabled multi-factor authentication, a defensive measure which is widely recommended in the industry, including by Microsoft itself.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Technical references for developers and articles for various Microsoft magazines such as *Microsoft Systems Journal* (*MSJ*) are available through the Microsoft Developer Network (MSDN).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] MSDN also offers subscriptions for companies and individuals, and the more expensive subscriptions usually offer access to pre-release beta versions of Microsoft software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In April 2004, Microsoft launched a community site for developers and users, titled Channel 9, that provides a wiki and an Internet forum.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Another community site that provides daily videocasts and other services, On10.net, launched on March 3, 2006.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Free technical support is traditionally provided through online Usenet newsgroups, and CompuServe in the past, monitored by Microsoft employees; there can be several newsgroups for a single product.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Helpful people can be elected by peers or Microsoft employees for Microsoft Most Valuable Professional (MVP) status, which entitles them to a sort of special social status and possibilities for awards and other benefits.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Noted for its internal lexicon, the expression "eating your own dog food" is used to describe the policy of using pre-release and beta versions of products inside Microsoft to test them in "real-world" situations.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] This is usually shortened to just "dog food" and is used as a noun, verb, and adjective.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Another bit of jargon, FYIFV or FYIV ("Fuck You, I'm [Fully] Vested"), is used by an employee to indicate they are financially independent and can avoid work anytime they wish.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft is an outspoken opponent of the cap on H-1B visas, which allows companies in the U.S. to employ certain foreign workers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Bill Gates claims the cap on H1B visas makes it difficult to hire employees for the company, stating "I'd certainly get rid of the H1B cap" in 2005.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Critics of H1B visas argue that relaxing the limits would result in increased unemployment for U.S. citizens due to H1B workers working for lower salaries.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The Human Rights Campaign Corporate Equality Index, a report of how progressive the organization deems company policies towards LGBT employees, rated Microsoft as 87% from 2002 to 2004 and as 100% from 2005 to 2010 after it allowed gender expression.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In August 2018, Microsoft implemented a policy for all companies providing subcontractors to require 12 weeks of paid parental leave to each employee.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] This expands on the former requirement from 2015 requiring 15 days of paid vacation and sick leave each year.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2015, Microsoft established its own parental leave policy to allow 12 weeks off for parental leave with an additional 8 weeks for the parent who gave birth.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2011, Greenpeace released a report rating the top ten big brands in cloud computing on the sources of electricity for their data centers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] At the time, data centers consumed up to 2% of all global electricity, and this amount was projected to increase.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2013, Microsoft agreed to buy power generated by a Texas wind project to power one of its data centers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft is ranked on the 17th place in Greenpeace's *Guide to Greener Electronics* (16th Edition) that ranks 18 electronics manufacturers according to its policies on toxic chemicals, recycling, and climate change.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft's timeline for phasing out brominated flame retardant (BFRs) and phthalates in all products was 2012 but its commitment to phasing out PVC is not clear.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] As of January 2011, it has no products that are completely free from PVC and BFRs.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft makes use of alternative forms of transit.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] It created one of the world's largest private bus systems, the "Connector", to transport people from outside the company; for on-campus transportation, the "Shuttle Connect" uses a large fleet of hybrid cars to save fuel.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The "Connector" does not compete with the public bus system and works with it to provide a cohesive transportation network not just for its employees but also for the public.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft also subsidizes regional public transport, provided by Sound Transit and King County Metro, as an incentive.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In February 2010, however, Microsoft took a stance against adding additional public transport and high-occupancy vehicle (HOV) lanes to the State Route 520 and its floating bridge connecting Redmond to Seattle; the company did not want to delay the construction any further.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft was ranked number 1 in the list of the World's Best Multinational Workplaces by the Great Place to Work Institute in 2011.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In January 2020, the company announced a strategy to take the company carbon negative by 2030 and to remove all carbon that it has emitted since its foundation in 1975.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] On October 9, 2020, Microsoft permanently allowed remote work.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In the same year, it was awarded the EPA's Green Power Leadership Award, citing the company's all-renewable energy use since 2014.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2023 Microsoft consumed 24 TWh of electricity, more than countries such as Iceland, Ghana, the Dominican Republic, or Tunisia.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The corporate headquarters, informally known as the Microsoft Redmond campus, is located at One Microsoft Way in Redmond, Washington.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft initially moved onto the grounds of the campus on February 26, 1986, weeks before the company went public on March 13.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The headquarters has since experienced multiple expansions since its establishment.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] It is estimated to encompass over 8 million ft2 (750,000 m2) of office space and 30,000–40,000 employees.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Additional offices are located in Bellevue and Issaquah, Washington (90,000 employees worldwide).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The company is planning to upgrade its Mountain View, California, campus on a grand scale.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The company has occupied this campus since 1981.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2016, the company bought the 32-acre (13 ha) campus, with plans to renovate and expand it by 25%.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft operates an East Coast headquarters in Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In April 2024, it was announced that Microsoft would be opening a state-of-the-art artificial intelligence 'hub' around Paddington in London, England.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] It was announced that the division would be led by Jordan Hoffman, who previously worked for Deepmind and Inflection.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] On October 26, 2015, the company opened its retail location on Fifth Avenue in New York City.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The location features a five-story glass storefront and is 22,270 square feet.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] As per company executives, Microsoft had been on the lookout for a flagship location since 2009.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The company's retail locations are part of a greater strategy to help build a connection with its consumers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The opening of the store coincided with the launch of the Surface Book and Surface Pro 4.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] On November 12, 2015, Microsoft opened a second flagship store, located in Sydney's Pitt Street Mall.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft adopted the so-called "*Pac-Man* Logo", designed by Scott Baker, on February 26, 1987, with the concept being similar to InFocus Corporation logo that was adapted a year earlier in 1986.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Baker stated "The new logo, in Helvetica italic typeface, has a slash between the *o* and *s* to emphasize the "soft" part of the name and convey motion and speed".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Dave Norris ran an internal joke campaign to save the old logo, which was green, in all uppercase, and featured a fanciful letter *O*, nicknamed the *blibbet*, but it was discarded.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft's logo with the tagline "Your potential.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Our passion."—below the main corporate name—is based on a slogan Microsoft used in 2008.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The new logo also includes four squares with the colors of the then-current Windows logo which have been used to represent Microsoft's four major products: Windows (blue), Office (orange), Xbox (green) and Bing (yellow).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The logo also resembles the opening of one of the commercials for Windows 95.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The company was the official jersey sponsor of Finland's national basketball team at EuroBasket 2015, a major sponsor of the Toyota Gazoo Racing WRT (2017–2020) and a sponsor of the Renault F1 Team (2016–2020).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2025, Microsoft was one of the donors who funded the demolition of the East Wing of the White House and planned building of a ballroom.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2015, Microsoft Philanthropies, an internal charitable organization, was established to bring the benefits of technology and the digital revolution to areas and groups that lack them.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Microsoft's president, Brad Smith, announced that it had donated an initial batch of supplies, including 15,000 protection goggles, infrared thermometers, medical caps, and protective suits, to healthcare workers in Seattle, with further aid to come.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Microsoft began monitoring cyberattacks originating from the Government of Russia and Russia-backed hackers.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In June 2022, Microsoft published the report on Russian cyber attacks and concluded that state-backed Russian hackers "have engaged in "strategic espionage" against governments, think tanks, businesses and aid groups" in 42 countries supporting Kyiv.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft also supports initiatives through its AI for Accessibility grant program, providing funding to various global organizations that create technologies to enhance accessibility for individuals with disabilities.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Among grant recipients from the Asia-Pacific region are the Sri Lankan IT company Fortude, the Thailand-based Vulcan Coalition, and the Indonesian organization Kerjabilitas.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Criticism of Microsoft has followed various aspects of its products and business practices, including surveillance of employees, "Velvet Sweatshop" practices, tax manipulation, and antitrust violations.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Frequently criticized are the ease of use, robustness, and security of the Microsoft's software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The company has also been criticized for the use of permatemp employees (employees employed for years as "temporary", and therefore without medical benefits), the use of forced retention tactics, which means that employees would be sued if they tried to leave.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Historically, Microsoft has also been accused of overworking employees, in many cases, leading to burnout within just a few years of joining the company.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The company is often referred to as a "Velvet Sweatshop", a term which originated in a 1989 *Seattle Times* article, and later became used to describe the company by some of Microsoft's own employees.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] This characterization is derived from the perception that Microsoft provides nearly everything for its employees in a convenient place, but in turn overworks them to a point where it would be bad for their (possibly long-term) health.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] As reported by several news outlets, an Irish subsidiary of Microsoft based in the Republic of Ireland declared £220 bn in profits but paid no corporation tax for the year 2020.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] This is due to the company being tax resident in Bermuda as mentioned in the accounts for 'Microsoft Round Island One, a subsidiary that collects license fees from the use of Microsoft software worldwide.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Dame Margaret Hodge, a Labour MP in the UK said, "It is unsurprising – yet still shocking – that massively wealthy global corporations openly, unashamedly and blatantly refuse to pay tax on the profits they make in the countries where they undertake business".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2020, ProPublica reported that the company had diverted more than $39 billion in U.S. profits to Puerto Rico using a mechanism structured to make it seem as if the company was unprofitable on paper.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] As a result, the company paid a tax rate on those profits of "nearly 0%".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] When the Internal Revenue Service audited these transactions, ProPublica reported that Microsoft aggressively fought back, including successfully lobbying Congress to change the law to make it harder for the agency to conduct audits of large corporations.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2023, Microsoft reported in a securities filing that the U.S.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Internal Revenue Service was alleging that the company owed the U.S. $28.9 billion in past taxes, plus penalties related to mis-allocation of corporate profits over a decade.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] "Embrace, extend, and extinguish" (EEE), also known as "embrace, extend, and exterminate," is a phrase that the U.S.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Department of Justice found that was used internally by Microsoft to describe its strategy for entering product categories involving widely used standards, extending those standards with proprietary capabilities, and then using those differences to strongly disadvantage competitors.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft was the first company to participate in the PRISM surveillance program, according to leaked NSA documents obtained by *The Guardian* and *The Washington Post* in June 2013, and acknowledged by government officials following the leak.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The program authorizes the government to secretly access data of non-US citizens hosted by American companies without a warrant.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft has denied participation in such a program.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In 2020, Salesforce, the manufacturer of the Slack platform, complained to European regulators about Microsoft due to the integration of the Teams service into Office 365.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Negotiations with the European Commission continued until the summer of 2023, but reached an impasse that led to Microsoft facing an antitrust investigation from the European Union.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In June 2024, Microsoft faced a potential EU fine after regulators accused it of abusing market power by bundling its Teams video-conferencing app with its Office 365 and Microsoft 365 software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The European Commission issued a statement of objections, alleging Microsoft's practice since 2019 gave Teams an unfair market advantage and limited interoperability with competing software.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] This action followed a 2019 complaint from Slack, which was later acquired by Salesforce.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft's Teams usage soared during the pandemic, growing from 2 million daily users in 2017 to 300 million in 2023.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The company has a history of antitrust battles in the U.S. and Europe, with over €2 billion in EU fines previously imposed for similar abuses.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In November 2024, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) launched an investigation into Microsoft, focusing on potential antitrust violations related to its cloud computing, AI, and cybersecurity businesses.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The probe scrutinized Microsoft's bundling of cloud services with products like Office and security tools, as well as its growing AI presence through its partnership with OpenAI.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] This inquiry was part of broader efforts by the U.S. government to enforce guidelines on the power of major tech companies.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Concerns were raised about Microsoft's licensing practices potentially locking customers into its services and its AI investments possibly sidestepping regulatory oversight.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft Azure is one of multiple cloud computing services used for data storage by the Israel Defense Forces (IDF).
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The IDF's usage of Azure intensified during the Gaza war and genocide, doubling its stored data to over 13.6 petabytes from March to July 2024.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] According to the complaint and media reports, Microsoft’s cloud services may have been used to store or process surveillance-related data.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The organization requested that European data protection authorities investigate whether this data processing complies with EU law.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In August 2025 a joint investigation by The Guardian, +972 Magazine, and Local Call reported that Microsoft Azure provides storage for mass-surveilled Palestinian phone calls to identify bombing targets in Gaza.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In September, in response to the investigation, Microsoft announced it had ended Azure access for the intelligence-focused Unit 8200 of the IDF.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In June 2025 Microsoft helped suspend the email account of Karim Ahmad Khan, a British International Criminal Court (ICC) prosecutor in the Netherlands who was investigating Israel for war crimes.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Microsoft was complying with a Trump executive order titled "Imposing Sanctions on the International Criminal Court".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] According to The New York Times, Microsoft's rapid compliance with the order, targeting an allied country, concerned European officials, and was seen as a symptom of the worsening relations between the U.S. and EU.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In October 2024, Microsoft fired two employees, software engineer Hossam Nasr and data scientist Abdo Mohamed, who organized an unauthorized vigil at its Redmond headquarters to honor Palestinians killed in the Gaza war.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The employees, part of the group No Azure for Apartheid, sought to address the company's involvement in the Israeli government's use of its technology.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In February 2025, the Associated Press reported that the Israeli military was utilizing Microsoft-developed artificial intelligence tools in its military and intelligence operations against the people of Gaza.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] In May 2025, Microsoft issued an unsigned statement confirming that these services had been made available to Israel, while denying that these tools were employed during the massacre of the people of Gaza.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] On March 20, 2025, before an event at Seattle's Great Hall with Brad Smith and Steve Ballmer, protestors projected "Microsoft powers genocide" on the wall.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] Subsequently, two employees, software engineers Ibtihal Aboussad and Vaniya Agrawal, interrupted AI executive Mustafa Suleyman at a speaking event on April 4, 2025, in protest at the company's support of Israel.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] After the disruptions at these events, Microsoft contacted the FBI in search of assistance in surveilling its pro-Palestinian employees and their allies.
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] The Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions movement added Microsoft to its list of targets for partnering "with the apartheid regime of Israel and its prison system".
[src:threadx-rtos/microsoft-p02] On August 20, 20 Microsoft employees and their allies were arrested after refusing to disperse from a protest on Microsoft's Redmond, Washington campus.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In computing, **preemption** is the act performed by an external scheduler — without assistance or cooperation from the task — of temporarily interrupting an executing task, with the intention of resuming it at a later time.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] This preemptive scheduler usually runs in the most privileged protection ring, meaning that interruption and then resumption are considered highly secure actions.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Such changes to the currently executing task of a processor are known as context switching.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In any given system design, some operations performed by the system may not be preemptable.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] This usually applies to kernel functions and service interrupts which, if not permitted to run to completion, would tend to produce race conditions resulting in deadlock.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Barring the scheduler from preempting tasks while they are processing kernel functions simplifies the kernel design at the expense of system responsiveness.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The distinction between user mode and kernel mode, which determines privilege level within the system, may also be used to distinguish whether a task is currently preemptable.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Most modern operating systems have **preemptive kernels**, which are designed to permit tasks to be preempted even when in kernel mode.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Examples of such operating systems are Solaris 2.0/SunOS 5.0, Windows NT, Linux kernel (2.5.4 and newer), AIX and some BSD systems (NetBSD, since version 5).
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The term **preemptive multitasking** is used to distinguish a multitasking operating system, which permits preemption of tasks, from a cooperative multitasking system wherein processes or tasks must be explicitly programmed to yield when they do not need system resources.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In simple terms: Preemptive multitasking involves the use of an interrupt mechanism which suspends the currently executing process and invokes a scheduler to determine which process should execute next.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Therefore, all processes will get some amount of CPU time at any given time.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In preemptive multitasking, the operating system kernel can also initiate a context switch to satisfy the scheduling policy's priority constraint, thus preempting the active task.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In general, preemption means "prior seizure of".
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] When the high-priority task at that instance seizes the currently running task, it is known as preemptive scheduling.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The term "preemptive multitasking" is sometimes mistakenly used when the intended meaning is more specific, referring instead to the class of scheduling policies known as *time-shared scheduling*, or *time-sharing*.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Preemptive multitasking allows the computer system to more reliably guarantee each process a regular "slice" of operating time.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] It also allows the system to rapidly deal with important external events like incoming data, which might require the immediate attention of one or another process.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] At any specific time, processes can be grouped into two categories: those that are waiting for input or output (called "I/O bound"), and those that are fully utilizing the CPU ("CPU bound").
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In early systems, processes would often "poll" or "busy-wait" while waiting for requested input (such as disk, keyboard or network input).
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] During this time, the process was not performing useful work, but still maintained complete control of the CPU.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] With the advent of interrupts and preemptive multitasking, these I/O bound processes could be "blocked", or put on hold, pending the arrival of the necessary data, allowing other processes to utilize the CPU.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] As the arrival of the requested data would generate an interrupt, blocked processes could be guaranteed a timely return to execution.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Although multitasking techniques were originally developed to allow multiple users to share a single machine, it became apparent that multitasking was useful regardless of the number of users.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Many operating systems, from mainframes down to single-user personal computers and no-user control systems (like those in robotic spacecraft), have recognized the usefulness of multitasking support for a variety of reasons.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Multitasking makes it possible for a single user to run multiple applications at the same time, or to run "background" processes while retaining control of the computer.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The period of time for which a process is allowed to run in a preemptive multitasking system is generally called the *time slice* or *quantum*.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The scheduler is run once every time slice to choose the next process to run.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The length of each time slice can be critical to balancing system performance vs process responsiveness - if the time slice is too short then the scheduler itself will consume too much processing time, but if the time slice is too long, processes will take longer to respond to input.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] An interrupt is scheduled to allow the operating system kernel to switch between processes when their time slices expire, effectively allowing the processor's time to be shared among a number of tasks, giving the illusion that it is dealing with these tasks in parallel (simultaneously).
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The operating system which controls such a design is called a multi-tasking system.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Today, nearly all operating systems support preemptive multitasking, including the current versions of Windows, Linux (including Android), and Darwin (including macOS and iOS).
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Sinclair QDOS and AmigaOS on the Amiga were also microcomputer operating systems offering preemptive multitasking as a core feature.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] These both ran on Motorola 68000-family microprocessors without memory management.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Amiga OS used dynamic loading of relocatable code blocks ("hunks" in Amiga jargon) to multitask preemptively all processes in the same flat address space.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Early operating systems for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS and PC DOS, did not support multitasking at all, however alternative operating systems such as MP/M-86 (1981) and Concurrent CP/M-86 did support preemptive multitasking.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Other Unix-like systems including MINIX and Coherent provided preemptive multitasking on 1980s-era personal computers.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Later MS-DOS compatible systems natively supporting preemptive multitasking/multithreading include Concurrent DOS, Multiuser DOS, Novell DOS (later called Caldera OpenDOS and DR-DOS 7.02 and higher).
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Since Concurrent DOS 386, they could also run multiple DOS programs concurrently in virtual DOS machines.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] The earliest version of Windows to support a limited form of preemptive multitasking was Windows/386 2.0, which used the Intel 80386's Virtual 8086 mode to run DOS applications in virtual 8086 machines, commonly known as "DOS boxes", which could be preempted.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In Windows 95, 98 and Me, 32-bit applications were made preemptive by running each one in a separate address space, but 16-bit applications remained cooperative for backward compatibility.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] In Windows 3.1x (protected mode), the kernel and virtual device drivers ran preemptively, but all 16-bit applications were non-preemptive and shared the same address space.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Preemptive multitasking has always been supported by Windows NT (all versions), OS/2 (native applications), Unix and Unix-like systems (such as Linux, BSD and macOS), VMS, OS/360, and many other operating systems designed for use in the academic and medium-to-large business markets.
[src:threadx-rtos/preemption-computing] Early versions of the classic Mac OS did not support multitasking at all, with cooperative multitasking becoming available via MultiFinder in System Software 5 and then standard in System 7.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] In real-time computing, **priority inheritance** is a method for eliminating unbounded priority inversion.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] Using this programming method, a process scheduling algorithm increases the priority of a process (A) to the maximum priority of any other process waiting for any resource on which A has a resource lock (if it is higher than the original priority of A).
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] The basic idea of the priority inheritance protocol is that when a job blocks one or more high-priority jobs, it ignores its original priority assignment and executes its critical section at an elevated priority level.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] After executing its critical section and releasing its locks, the process returns to its original priority level.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] Suppose that both H and L require some shared resource.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] If L acquires this shared resource (entering a critical section), and H subsequently requires it, H will block until L releases it (leaving its critical section).
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] Without priority inheritance, process M could preempt process L during the critical section and delay its completion, in effect causing the lower-priority process M to indirectly preempt the high-priority process H.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] With priority inheritance, L will execute its critical section at H's high priority whenever H is blocked on the shared resource.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] As a result, M will be unable to preempt L and will be blocked.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] That is, the higher-priority job M must wait for the critical section of the lower priority job L to be executed, because L has inherited H's priority.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] When L exits its critical section, it regains its original (low) priority and awakens H (which was blocked by L).
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] H, having high priority, preempts L and runs to completion.
[src:threadx-rtos/priority-inheritance] This enables M and L to resume in succession and run to completion without priority inversion.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:threadx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] In 1997, **ThreadX** was first released and marketed by Express Logic of San Diego, California, United States.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It was developed by William Lamie, who was also the original author of Nucleus and PX5 RTOS, and was president and CEO of Express Logic.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX version 4 was introduced in 2001, version 5 was introduced in 2005, and then version 6 was introduced in 2020 (the latest major version).
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] FileX – the embedded file system for ThreadX was introduced in 1999.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] NetX – the embedded TCP/IP networking stack for ThreadX was introduced in 2002.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] USBX – the embedded USB support for ThreadX was introduced in 2004.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX SMP for SMP multi-core environments was introduced in 2009.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX achieved safety certifications for: TÜV IEC 61508 in 2013, and UL 60730 in 2014.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] GUIX – the embedded UI for ThreadX was introduced in 2014.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] On April 18, 2019, Microsoft purchased Express Logic for an undisclosed sum and it was renamed to **Azure RTOS**.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] On November 21, 2023, Microsoft announced Azure RTOS would be transitioning to an open source model under the stewardship of the Eclipse Foundation, and making the project available under the permissive MIT License.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] With Eclipse Foundation as the new home, Azure RTOS was renamed to **Eclipse ThreadX**, or "ThreadX" in its short form.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] The name ThreadX refers to the threads used as the executable elements, with *X* representing context switching.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX provides priority-based, pre-emptive scheduling; fast interrupt response; memory management; interthread communication; mutual exclusion; event notification; and thread synchronization features.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] Major distinguishing technological characteristics of ThreadX include a preemption-threshold, priority inheritance, efficient timer management, fast software timers, picokernel design, event-chaining, and small size (minimal size on an ARM architecture processor is about 2 KB).
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX supports multi-core processor environments via either asymmetric multiprocessing (AMP) or symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] Application thread isolation with memory management unit (MMU) or memory protection unit (MPU) memory protection is available with ThreadX Modules.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX has safety certifications from TÜV and UL and is Motor Industry Software Reliability Association and MISRA C compliant.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX is the foundation of Express Logic's X-Ware Internet of things (IoT) platform, which includes embedded file system support (FileX), embedded UI support (GUIX), embedded Internet protocol suite (TCP/IP), cloud connectivity (NetX/NetX Duo), and Universal Serial Bus (USB) support (USBX).
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX is liked by developers and is a popular RTOS.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] As of 2017, ThreadX RTOS has become one of the most popular RTOSs in the world, deployed in over 6.2 billion devices, including consumer electronics, medical devices, data networking applications, and SoCs.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX implements a priority-based, pre-emptive scheduling algorithm with a proprietary feature called preemption-threshold.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] The threshold provides greater granularity within critical sections, reduces context switching, and has been the subject of academic research on guaranteeing scheduling.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX provides a unique construct called event chaining, where the application can register a callback function on all APIs that can signal an external event.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] This helps applications chain together various public objects in ThreadX allowing one thread to block on multiple objects.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX also provides counting semaphores, mutexes with optional priority inheritance, event flags, message queues, software timers, fixed-sized block memory, and variable-sized block memory.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] All APIs in ThreadX that block on resources also have an optional timeout.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX offers multi-core processor support via either AMP or SMP.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] Application code isolation is available through the ThreadX Modules component.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX (and FileX and NetX Duo) have been precertified by SGS-TÜV Saar to the following safety standards: IEC 61508 SIL 4, IEC 62304 Class C, ISO 26262 ASIL D, and EN 50128 SW-SIL 4.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX has also been certified to DO-178 standards by various military and aerospace companies.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It is supported by popular Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) libraries such as wolfSSL.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] As of 2017, ThreadX is packaged as part of X-Ware IoT Platform in full source code and with no runtime royalty payment.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] ThreadX is the real-time operating system (RTOS).
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] FileX is an optional file system for ThreadX.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It supports FAT12, FAT16, FAT32, and exFAT file systems.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] The latter extends FAT file sizes beyond 4 GB, which is useful for large video files.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It also offers fault tolerance and supports direct NOR and NAND flash memory media through an optional flash wear leveling product called **LevelX**.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] GUIX is an optional graphical user interface (GUI) for ThreadX.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It provides a 2D computer graphics system that supports multiple display devices with a variety of screen resolutions and color depths.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] Many predefined graphical widgets are available.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] A Windows WYSIWYG host tool called GUIX Studio automatically generates C code for GUIX to execute at runtime.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] NetX Duo is an optional TCP/IP network system for ThreadX.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It supports both IPv4 and IPv6 networking with IPsec network security.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] TCP and UDP socket layers are provided by TLS / DTLS.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] Optional protocols include ARP, Auto IP, DHCP, DNS, DNS-SD, FTP, HTTP, ICMP, IGMP, mDNS, POP3, PPP, PPPoE, RARP, TFTP, SNTP, SMTP, SNMP, and Telnet.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] IoT Cloud protocol support includes CoAP, MQTT, and LWM2M.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] NetX Duo also supports Thread and 6LoWPAN.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] In 2017, ThreadX and NetX Duo became a Thread Certified Product.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] USBX is an optional Universal Serial Bus (USB) system for ThreadX.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It supports both host/device/on-the-go (OTG).
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] Host controller support includes EHCI, OHCI, and proprietary USB host controllers.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] It supports these USB Device Classes: Audio, Asix, CDC/ACM, CDC/ECM, DFU, GSER, HID, PIMA, Printer, Prolific, RNDIS, and Storage.
[src:threadx-rtos/threadx] TraceX is an optional host software that provides a graphical view of ThreadX RTOS events.
